author: London 'flash crash' trader indicted by US federal grand jury
title: WiseTech holds fire on IPO
text:
WiseTech has pushed back its initial public offering plans until 2016. by Sarah Thompson Anthony Macdonald Jake Mitchell WiseTech Global has pushed its ASX listing back to the first quarter of 2016 as it focuses on hoovering up competitors in key markets.
Sources said the company, which raised $35 million earlier this year from cornerstone investors, including Fidelity and Smallco, was using its strong balance sheet to acquire customers and operations for its supply chain execution platform, CargoWise One.
WiseTech recently snapped up acquired ZSoft, a leading freight-forwarding software provider in China, and is in the process of taking over JSE-listed, Compu-Clearing in South Africa via a scheme of arrangement.
The company was founded by Richard White in Sydney in the mid 1990's. Scott Colvin is advising the board, and Credit Suisse and Morgan Stanley are lined up to pull the trigger on an IPO.
Elsewhere, former JPMorgan oil and gas analyst Benjamin Wilson has joined RBC Capital Markets. He has replaced former RBC energy analyst Andrew Williams.
The news comes after Street Talk revealed RBC had nabbed former CIMB head of research Andrew Scott to head of the Canadian bank's local industrials research team, with a focus on building material and chemicals.
